  <chapter number="5" style="c" sid="HEB 5" />
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="1" style="v" sid="HEB 5:1" />The fact of the matter is that every high priest drawn from the pool of human beings for the benefit
        of mankind is appointed to a position <char style="it">in regard to</char> those things pertaining to
        God in order to offer offerings, plus sacrifices on top of that, on behalf of sinners, <verse eid="HEB 5:1" />
      <verse number="2" style="v" sid="HEB 5:2" />being able to moderate his feelings, restrain himself, and be gentle to the ignorant, to those who lack
        understanding, to those who are mistaken, and to those who’ve gone astray, since he too is engulfed in
        <char style="it">human</char> frailty<char style="sup">[a]</char>, <verse eid="HEB 5:2" />
      <verse number="3" style="v" sid="HEB 5:3" />and because of <char style="it">this</char> same frailty, just like what affects the folk-people, he’s
        obliged just the same to offer up offerings over and over again in matters where his own sins are involved.<verse eid="HEB 5:3" />
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="4" style="v" sid="HEB 5:4" />Furthermore,<char style="it"> </char>any-old person can’t do the honor and appoint himself to the position
        <char style="it">of high priest</char>, but instead the one called by God <char style="it">to be a high
        priest </char>gets <char style="it">to be appointed</char> just like Aaron was <char style="it">appointed</char>.<verse eid="HEB 5:4" />
      <verse number="5" style="v" sid="HEB 5:5" />In the same way Christ didn’t become a high priest in a self-aggrandizing manner—uh-uh—<char style="it">his
        appointment was in line with</char> what was spoken<char style="it"> </char>to him:</para>
    <para style="pi" vid="HEB 5:5"></para>
    <para style="pi" vid="HEB 5:5">You are My son</para>
    <para style="pi" vid="HEB 5:5">Today I have begotten you<verse eid="HEB 5:5"/>
    </para>
    <para style="pi" />    <!-- Spacer line. No verse associated with it. -->
    <para style="m">
      <verse number="6" style="v" sid="HEB 5:6" /><char style="it">This is</char> also consistent with what a different <char style="it">verse</char> says:</para>
    <para style="pi" vid="HEB 5:6"></para>
    <para style="pi" vid="HEB 5:6">You are a priest <char style="it">and will be one </char>forevermore</para>
    <para style="pi" vid="HEB 5:6">According to the order of Melchizedek<verse eid="HEB 5:6"/>
    </para>
    <para style="pi" />    <!-- Spacer line. No verse associated with it. -->
    <para style="m">
      <verse number="7" style="v" sid="HEB 5:7" />Who, during the time when he had a human body<char style="sup">[b]</char>, offered up <char style="it">an
        offering of </char>prayers plus humble, earnest, urgent requests for protection<char style="sup">[A]</char>
        on top of that to the One having the power to continually rescue and protect him from death, <char style="it">praying</char>
        with loud<char style="sup">[c]</char> crying and tears, and he was listened to and heeded because of
        the reverent awe he had in the presence of God. <verse eid="HEB 5:7" />
      <verse number="8" style="v" sid="HEB 5:8" />Although he was a son, he learned the obedience <char style="it">required of him </char>from the things
        he suffered, <verse eid="HEB 5:8" />
      <verse number="9" style="v" sid="HEB 5:9" />and once the items of obedience <char style="it">that were required of</char> him<char style="it"> </char>were
        finished, he became a source of eternal salvation<char style="sup">[d]</char>, <verse eid="HEB 5:9" />
      <verse number="10" style="v" sid="HEB 5:10" />designated by God <char style="it">to be </char>a high priest after the order of Melchizedek.<verse eid="HEB 5:10" />
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="11" style="v" sid="HEB 5:11" />There’s a lot <char style="it">we were wanting to go over with you</char> on this topic, and it’s difficult
        to explain <char style="it">anything</char> to you since you’ve gotten to where you don’t listen very
        well. <verse eid="HEB 5:11" />
      <verse number="12" style="v" sid="HEB 5:12" />In fact, you should be teachers by this time, <char style="it">but instead </char>you need to have someone
        <char style="it">come and </char>teach you the fundamentals<char style="sup">[e]</char><char style="sup">[B]</char>
        of the word<char style="sup">[f]</char> of God all over again, and have gotten to where you require milk
        and can’t<char style="it"> handle </char>solid food. <verse eid="HEB 5:12" />
      <verse number="13" style="v" sid="HEB 5:13" />You see, anyone who’s on a milk-only diet has not demonstrated competency<char style="sup">[g]</char>
        in those things which have their origin in the subject of righteousness: he’s an infant, you see. <verse eid="HEB 5:13" />
      <verse number="14" style="v" sid="HEB 5:14" />But solid food is for grown-ups, who in the course of <char style="it">their </char>maturity have developed
        and trained <char style="it">their</char> faculties of perception to distinguish both good and bad<char
        style="sup">[C]</char>.<verse eid="HEB 5:14" />
    </para>
