  <!--   Chapter 11   -->
  <!--   **********   -->
  <chapter number="11" style="c" sid="HEB 11" />
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="1" style="v" sid="HEB 11:1" />Faith is<char style="sup">[A]</char> the undergirding of what’s hoped for, the proof of things not seen
        (which includes all things for which there is no physical evidence); <verse eid="HEB 11:1" />
      <verse number="2" style="v" sid="HEB 11:2" />by this, you see, those we hold in esteem from long ago<char style="sup">[a]</char> had an official account,
        a favorable mention, of their actions recorded for posterity.<verse eid="HEB 11:2" />
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="3" style="v" sid="HEB 11:3" />By faith our mind understands that the world was set in order by a sentence spoken by God, resulting
        in what we see coming into being out of what hasn’t been manifested.<verse eid="HEB 11:3" />
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="4" style="v" sid="HEB 11:4" />By faith Abel offered God a much <char style="it">better </char>sacrifice than Cain, through which an
        attestation to him being righteous was entered <char style="it">into the official record</char>, the
        record specifying the gifts he offered to God, and through <char style="it">his faith</char>, <char style="it">though</char>
        he’s dead he’s still speaking.<verse eid="HEB 11:4" />
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="5" style="v" sid="HEB 11:5" />By faith Enoch was instantaneously transported from one place to another for the purpose of not experiencing<char
        style="sup">[b]</char> death; “There was no trace of him to be found<char style="sup">[c]</char> because
        God had transported him.” You see, before he was transported, it had been stated for the record that
        he had pleased God quite well.<verse eid="HEB 11:5" />
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="6" style="v" sid="HEB 11:6" />Now apart from faith it’s impossible to be well-pleasing to God, for he who approaches God must believe
        (and have already believed ahead of time)<char style="sup">[d]</char> that He is <char style="it">the
        Great I Am</char> and that a reward manifests itself <char style="it">and is awarded </char>to those
        who seek Him out.<verse eid="HEB 11:6" />
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="7" style="v" sid="HEB 11:7" />By faith Noah, having been warned by God about things that had not yet been seen, in piety and in the
        fear of God built and provisioned an ark for the purpose of preserving his family and keeping it safe,
        through which <char style="it">faith</char> he condemned the world (i.e., consigned the world to punishment)
        and became an heir of the righteousness which comes from faith.<verse eid="HEB 11:7" />
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="8" style="v" sid="HEB 11:8" />By faith Abraham obeyed when he was summoned to leave <char style="it">the place he lived and </char>go
        to <char style="it">the place </char>which he was going to receive as an inheritance (i.e., a place which
        was reserved for him exclusively and in perpetuity), and he departed having no idea where he was going.<verse eid="HEB 11:8" />
      <verse number="9" style="v" sid="HEB 11:9" />By faith he emigrated and became a foreign resident in the land of promise, living in tents with Isaac
        and Jacob, joint-heirs of the same promise. <verse eid="HEB 11:9" />
      <verse number="10" style="v" sid="HEB 11:10" />You see, he anticipated, expected, and was eagerly awaiting the city which is not a rickety-rackety,
        makeshift one but is built to last<char style="sup">[e]</char>, whose builder and architect is God.<verse eid="HEB 11:10" />
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="11" style="v" sid="HEB 11:11" />By faith, even Sarah, who couldn’t have children, got the ability to conceive in her old age, since she
        considered the One Who had promised to be faithful. <verse eid="HEB 11:11" />
      <verse number="12" style="v" sid="HEB 11:12" />As this was the case, one man (and this fellow was debilitated<char style="sup">[f]</char>) sired <char
        style="it">a nation </char>as innumerable as the stars in the sky and the grains of sand on the beach.<verse eid="HEB 11:12" />
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="13" style="v" sid="HEB 11:13" />All these <char style="it">people </char>died in sync with<char style="it"> </char>faith, not having
        received the promises, but having seen and greeted them from afar instead, and having confessed that
        they were foreigners on this planet. <verse eid="HEB 11:13" />
      <verse number="14" style="v" sid="HEB 11:14" />The fact is, those who say such things make it evident that they seek their native country. <verse eid="HEB 11:14" />
      <verse number="15" style="v" sid="HEB 11:15" />If they kept on rehashing memories of<char style="it"> fondness for</char> that <char style="it">ungodly
        </char>place they ventured forth from, they would have found<char style="sup">[g]</char> an opportunity
        <char style="it">or made an excuse</char> to return; <verse eid="HEB 11:15" />
      <verse number="16" style="v" sid="HEB 11:16" />but as it stands, they aspire for better, that is to say, for <char style="it">something</char> from
        the spiritual domain or from heaven. In light of this, God is not ashamed to be called their God, for
        He has prepared a city for them.<verse eid="HEB 11:16" />
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="17" style="v" sid="HEB 11:17" />By faith Abraham, while being tested, offered up Isaac—he who gladly received the promises offered up
        his one and only <char style="it">son</char>, <verse eid="HEB 11:17" />
      <verse number="18" style="v" sid="HEB 11:18" />to whom it was spoken, “The descendants who will perpetuate your family tree will be designated as coming
        through Isaac.<char style="sup">[h]</char>” <verse eid="HEB 11:18" />
      <verse number="19" style="v" sid="HEB 11:19" /><char style="it">Abraham </char>figured that, in addition <char style="it">to the promises He already
        made,</char> God is able to raise <char style="it">someone </char>from the dead. As a result of this,
        he recovered <char style="it">Isaac from the dead</char> in an analogous fashion.<verse eid="HEB 11:19" />
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="20" style="v" sid="HEB 11:20" />Also by faith Isaac pronounced blessings over Jacob and Esau in regard to what would happen <char style="it">to
        them </char>in the future.<verse eid="HEB 11:20" />
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="21" style="v" sid="HEB 11:21" />By faith Jacob while on his death bed pronounced blessings over the sons of Joseph, and “bowed down <char
        style="it">in worship</char> <char style="it">leaning</char> on top of his staff<char style="sup">[B]</char>.”<verse eid="HEB 11:21" />
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="22" style="v" sid="HEB 11:22" />By faith Joseph, nearing the end, left a reminder about the Exodus with the descendants of Israel and
        left orders about his bones (i.e., orders that they take his bones with them when they leave).<verse eid="HEB 11:22" />
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="23" style="v" sid="HEB 11:23" />By faith Moses was hidden by his parents after he was born out of a reverential fear because they saw
        that the boy had charisma<char style="sup">[i]</char>, and they didn’t fear the king’s decree. <verse eid="HEB 11:23" />
      <verse number="24" style="v" sid="HEB 11:24" />By faith Moses <char style="it">grew up and</char> became a great man and renounced his claim of being
        the son of Pharaoh’s daughter, <verse eid="HEB 11:24" />
      <verse number="25" style="v" sid="HEB 11:25" />having chosen to endure the hardship with God’s folk rather than to retain the pleasures of sin for a
        brief span of time, <verse eid="HEB 11:25" />
      <verse number="26" style="v" sid="HEB 11:26" />considering the vilification and reviling of Christ to be greater riches than the treasures of Egypt;
        for he was focused on the reward.<verse eid="HEB 11:26" />
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="27" style="v" sid="HEB 11:27" />By faith he left Egypt, unafraid of the wrath of <char style="it">Pharaoh</char> the king, for he endured
        as <char style="it">one</char> seeing the Unseen-One. <verse eid="HEB 11:27" />
      <verse number="28" style="v" sid="HEB 11:28" />By faith he observed the Passover and the marking of the blood, <char style="it">done</char> so that
        the Destroyer wouldn’t touch any of their firstborn <char style="it">sons</char>. <verse eid="HEB 11:28" />
      <verse number="29" style="v" sid="HEB 11:29" />By faith he crossed the Red Sea as if it was dry land; when the Egyptians tried <char style="it">to cross
        </char>it, they were drowned.<verse eid="HEB 11:29" />
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="30" style="v" sid="HEB 11:30" />By faith the walls of Jericho fell after being <char style="it">marched around </char>in a circle for
        seven days.<verse eid="HEB 11:30" />
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="31" style="v" sid="HEB 11:31" />By faith, the prostitute Rahab wasn’t wiped out with those who were disobedient after extending a welcome
        to the spies and taking them in<char style="sup">[j]</char>.<verse eid="HEB 11:31" />
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="32" style="v" sid="HEB 11:32" />And what more will I say? For there’s not enough time to go into detail about Gideon, Barak, Samson,
        Jephthah, David, plus Solomon and the prophets, <verse eid="HEB 11:32" />
      <verse number="33" style="v" sid="HEB 11:33" />who through faith conquered kingdoms, put into practice standards of fairness <char style="it">while
        ruling</char>, obtained promises, shut the mouths of lions, <verse eid="HEB 11:33" />
      <verse number="34" style="v" sid="HEB 11:34" />extinguished intense heat-generating fires<char style="sup">[k]</char>, escaped <char style="it">the</char>
        sword’s edge, got their strength back from weakness, became mighty men in war, routed foreign armies
        in battle. <verse eid="HEB 11:34" />
      <verse number="35" style="v" sid="HEB 11:35" />Women got <char style="it">members of</char> their <char style="it">family</char> who died to come back
        to life. Others were tortured but refused the chance to get out of it, so that they would be better off
        in their life after death<char style="sup">[l]</char>. <verse eid="HEB 11:35" />
      <verse number="36" style="v" sid="HEB 11:36" />Others experienced jeering and whipping; still others <char style="it">experienced </char>being chained
        up and locked up. <verse eid="HEB 11:36" />
      <verse number="37" style="v" sid="HEB 11:37" />They were stoned to death, they were sawn <char style="it">in two</char>, they were tempted and brought
        to the breaking point, they were slain by the sword, they wandered about in sheepskins, in goatskins,
        while being impoverished, afflicted, distressed, mistreated— <verse eid="HEB 11:37" />
      <verse number="38" style="v" sid="HEB 11:38" /><char style="it">people</char> whom the world is not worthy of—<char style="it">They lived in </char>deserts,
        on mountains, in caves, in underground tunnels—<verse eid="HEB 11:38" />
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="39" style="v" sid="HEB 11:39" />Because of their faith all of these people had a favorable account of <char style="it">their exploits</char>
        recorded for posterity’s sake but did not obtain the promise, <verse eid="HEB 11:39" />
      <verse number="40" style="v" sid="HEB 11:40" />God having provided something better for us, so that <char style="it">their ranks</char> would not be
        complete without us <char style="it">added</char>.<verse eid="HEB 11:40" />
    </para>
